You are building Mirsa — a hackathon demo web application for Alzheimer's caregivers.

## Project context
- App name: Mirsa
- Patient: Robert
- Primary caregiver: Margaret  
- Secondary caregiver: Sarah
- PRD is in PRD.md — read it before making any decisions

## Stack rules — never deviate
- Next.js 14 App Router only — no Pages Router
- TypeScript strict mode — zero `any` types, zero suppressions
- Tailwind CSS for all styling — no inline style objects except where Tailwind cannot reach
- shadcn/ui for all UI components — do not build from scratch what shadcn provides
- Supabase for all data — no other database calls
- Claude claude-sonnet-4-5 for all AI — no other models
- No authentication — DEMO_MODE=true bypasses all auth checks

## Code quality rules — enforced on every file
- Every async function has try/catch error handling
- Every Supabase query checks the error field: `const { data, error } = await supabase...` then `if (error) throw error`
- Every API route returns a typed NextResponse — no implicit any in response shapes
- Loading states on every async action — no UI that freezes silently
- Zero console.log in production code — use proper error handling

## The classifier route is safety-critical
- Claude returns JSON only: {match: string|null, confidence: number}
- Confidence < 0.85 always returns null
- Any non-JSON response always returns null
- Returned label always validated against the known anchor allowlist
- No conversation history ever passed to the classifier
- Any error always returns {match: null, confidence: 0} — never a 500

## Device page rules — iPad Safari
- Web Speech API requires a user gesture on iOS — always gate behind Start Mirsa button
- Use voiceschanged event for TTS voice selection — never synchronous getVoices()
- Use Screen Wake Lock API to prevent screen sleep — re-acquire on visibility change
- No requestFullscreen() — use PWA manifest + apple-mobile-web-app-capable instead
- No scrolling, no bounce, no browser chrome visible
- Landscape optimised

## Design rules
- Device page background: #0d0d0b
- Caregiver app background: #faf9f6
- Accent: #2d9e75 (teal)
- Alert: #d97706 (amber)
- Fonts: Lora serif for emotional/display text, DM Sans for UI
- Border radius: 16px minimum on cards
- Touch targets: 48px minimum height
- Max width: 430px on caregiver app
- Empty states: warm human copy — never "No data found"

## The four demo moments — never break these
1. Device answers "Where are my keys?" in warm voice with photo surfacing
2. Caregiver app receives real-time alert within 2 seconds of elevated anchor trigger
3. Unmatched question → teach-this → device answers immediately (no refresh)
4. Weekly summary reads as a compassionate letter in Lora serif

## Mirsa never generates content spoken to Robert
- The classify route returns a key only
- The device retrieves stored response_text from local anchor cache
- Claude never speaks as a source of truth about Robert's life
- This is architectural — enforce it in code, not just in prompts

## Landing page
The app has a public marketing landing page at `/` (root route).
It is separate from /demo, /device, and /app.
It explains Mirsa to anyone who visits the URL — judges, investors, the public.
It must be visually exceptional — the single most impressive-looking page in the entire project.